				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Good duo class with bard<a name="48029"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jun 24 04 12:15 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>You can't go wrong with a beastlord.
<br />

<br />
I've found if there's one thing sorta lacking when playing my bard, and this is not a complaint by any means because I do love my bard's capabilities, is out-n-out dps. The bst will provide this in spades. With the bst and his/her pet you'll pretty much have three more-than-adequate tanks at your disposal. The bst does also provide some nice buffs, mainly gotten from the shaman line (haste at later levels, slow, stat buffs), some nice AA's (Paragon) and the best pet heals in the game. The pet really is a monster, second only to the mage and arguably a better tank than the mage pet. The pet procs are amazing.
<br />

<br />
I have a lot of fun playing my bst and bard (two-boxing on same machine). I play the bst as the primary character with my bard playing hp/mana song, meleeing, and doing a little crowd control and pulling when needed. As a true duo you'll be capable of a lot more, twisting in damage shield and shield of songs type spells etc for better efficiency.
<br />

<br />
I did two-box my shaman and bard when they were both levels 18-42 or so until I decided to make a big push on my bard to get into the 50's. In that combo my bard was the primary character,  with my shaman throwing in a couple of DD's and DoT's, sending in pet, and buffing. I used a mixture of straight-up tanking and fear-kiting. I do really like my shaman but the kills will be slower in comparison to grouping with a beastlord because your dps will not be the same.</span></td>
